{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504343"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2323"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2323"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.08,0.04,0.51,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48853"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2323"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33847"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"1390"},{"type":"tags","id":"1396"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12534"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48853"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a five-day history of right-sided nasal obstruction, nasal deformity and minor bilateral epistaxis following an injury to his nose. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On the day of injury, he was assessed in the Emergency Department and diagnosed with an acute fracture of the nasal bones. No other facial or intracranial injuries were identified at that time. On examination today, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The nasal dorsum is deviated to the right and the nasal septum is deviated to the right. No neurological deficits or other bony injuries are identified.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the patient\u0027s current symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Septal haematoma","Nasal bone fracture","Nasal septal perforation","Deviation of a fractured nasal septum","Inferior turbinate bone fracture"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an acute, uncomplicated nasal fracture with unilateral nasal obstruction, which is most likely attributed to \u003Cstrong\u003Edeviation of a fractured nasal septum\u003C/strong\u003E. This is more likely to cause unilateral obstruction once initial swelling improves after approximately five days.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptal haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious complication of nasal trauma and is likely to cause bilateral nasal obstruction. It occurs following rupture of blood vessels supplying the septal cartilage and collection of blood between the avascular cartilage and the overlying mucosa. Left untreated, the septal cartilage may become infected or undergo ischaemic necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enasal bone fracture\u003C/strong\u003E alone, without involvement of the septum, is less likely to cause persistent unilateral obstruction. The nasal bones form the bony upper third of the nose.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enasal septal perforation\u003C/strong\u003E may occur following nasal trauma but would not typically cause unilateral obstruction. Patients may report crusting, whistling, or a feeling of nasal congestion.\u003C/p\u003E\n  \n\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior turbinate bone fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is very unlikely in this case. The inferior turbinates are made of bone covered by soft tissue and do not typically fracture in nasal injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Persistent unilateral nasal obstruction after a nasal injury is likely to be due to septal deviation."],"references":["Koh J, Bhatti O, Mahmood A, Agar N. Traumatic nasal injuries in general practice. Australian Family Physician. 2016;45:650-3. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27606367/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33847"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2323"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33847"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-18T21:00:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-18T21:00:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2323"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48853"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","